{"cursor":"11791","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{Infobox Disease\n | Name = Blister Image = Smlp6860.jpg Caption = Blister on foot caused by\n | wearing flip flops.,,crg DiseasesDB = 1777 ICD10 = ICD9 = ICDO = OMIM =\n | MedlinePlus = 003239 eMedicineSubj = eMedicineTopic = MeshID = D001768\n}} A 'blister' is a small pocket of fluid within the upper layers of the skin,\ntypically caused by forceful rubbing (friction), burning, freezing, chemical\nexposure or infection. Most blisters are filled with a clear fluid called serum\nor plasma. However, blisters can be filled with\nblood (known as blood blisters) or with pus (if they become infected).\n\nThe word \"blister\" entered English in the 14th century. It came from the Middle\nDutch \"bluyster\", and was a modification of the Old French \"blostre\" which meant\na leprous noduleâa rise in the skin due to leprosy.\n","linknr":344,"url":"Blister","recorded":1362581278,"links":49,"instances":["dermatology","skin"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Skin conditions resulting from physical factors","Radiation health effects"],"headings":["Causes","Prevention","Treatment","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f8/Wiktionary-logo-en.svg/37px-Wiktionary-logo-en.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0a/Smlp6860.jpg/230px-Smlp6860.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/Friction_Blisters_On_Human_Foot.jpg/220px-Friction_Blisters_On_Human_Foot.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/01/Ampolla.jpg/170px-Ampolla.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Blister-arm.jpg/220px-Blister-arm.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/ce/Foot_blis